within your database.


490
00:22:07,286 --> 00:22:10,396
Let's talk a little bit
about account management.


491
00:22:10,396 --> 00:22:14,556
When a particular administrator
provides their credentials,


492
00:22:14,556 --> 00:22:18,126
their VPP account to your
solution, and you want


493
00:22:18,126 --> 00:22:19,346
to establish that
initial connection


494
00:22:19,346 --> 00:22:22,546
with the Volume Purchase
Program you're going to need


495
00:22:22,546 --> 00:22:24,306
to check the client
context attribute.


496
00:22:24,896 --> 00:22:26,796
And if it's empty that means


497
00:22:26,796 --> 00:22:29,106
that no other server
has claimed this account


498
00:22:29,106 --> 00:22:30,156
or is using this account.


499
00:22:30,486 --> 00:22:31,656
And you should go
ahead and claim it


500
00:22:31,656 --> 00:22:35,766
by providing the host name of
your server and a unique a GUID


501
00:22:35,766 --> 00:22:38,426
so that you'll be able to tell
whether your server is still the


502
00:22:38,426 --> 00:22:39,066
one managing.


503
00:22:40,296 --> 00:22:42,506
If the client context
has a value


504
00:22:42,506 --> 00:22:45,326
and it doesn't match the GUID
that you have for that server,


505
00:22:45,666 --> 00:22:47,876
some other server is
actually using that account.


506
00:22:47,876 --> 00:22:49,876
And you're going to want
to alert the administrator


507
00:22:49,876 --> 00:22:52,936
that some other server is
managing the licenses tied


508
00:22:52,936 --> 00:22:56,786
to this account and ask them
to confirm that they, in fact,


509
00:22:56,786 --> 00:22:58,506
want this server to
take over that account.


510
00:22:58,896 --> 00:23:01,356
That may, in fact, be the right
thing if they're transitioning


511
00:23:01,356 --> 00:23:02,796
from one server to the next.


512
00:23:03,286 --> 00:23:06,766
And then further, whenever you
re establish the connection


513
00:23:06,766 --> 00:23:09,816
to the service, you need to
check client context again


514
00:23:09,816 --> 00:23:12,826
to make sure that your server is
still the one that's connected


515
00:23:12,826 --> 00:23:13,526
to this account.


516
00:23:14,286 --> 00:23:16,416
If it doesn't match
any longer, you, again,


517
00:23:16,466 --> 00:23:18,706
need to stop making
requests to the service


518
00:23:18,926 --> 00:23:20,346
and alert the administrator


519
00:23:20,346 --> 00:23:23,436
that this other host name
has now claimed this account


520
00:23:23,436 --> 00:23:24,926
so they can take
appropriate action.


521
00:23:27,326 --> 00:23:29,146
If I've mentioned
invitations already,


522
00:23:29,526 --> 00:23:32,466
that's part of bootstrapping
this program is


523
00:23:32,466 --> 00:23:35,336
that the administrator
needs it to invite each user


524
00:23:35,336 --> 00:23:39,116
to link their Apple ID to
this particular VPP account


525
00:23:39,506 --> 00:23:41,206
so that licenses
can be assigned.


526
00:23:42,016 --> 00:23:45,386
We strongly recommend that you
do this invitation via MDM.


527
00:23:46,016 --> 00:23:46,986
You can easily send


528
00:23:46,986 --> 00:23:48,986
that invitation via an
MDM command directly


529
00:23:48,986 --> 00:23:50,006
to an enrolled device.


530
00:23:50,006 --> 00:23:52,526
It's much more secure
and reliable.


531
00:23:53,416 --> 00:23:56,886
Email is a fall back if you
have a user you need to invite


532
00:23:56,886 --> 00:23:58,636
that doesn't currently
have an enrolled device.


533
00:23:59,986 --> 00:24:02,636
But there's a concern that
you need to be aware of that


534
00:24:02,636 --> 00:24:05,616
because the invitation URL,
there's an example on screen,


535
00:24:06,026 --> 00:24:08,356
is for the apple.com domain.


536
00:24:08,996 --> 00:24:12,186
Many mail servers will
treat an email coming


537
00:24:12,186 --> 00:24:15,986
from your server's domain,
including a URL from apple.com


538
00:24:15,986 --> 00:24:18,136
as a phishing attack and
they filter them out.


539
00:24:18,936 --> 00:24:20,526
There are a number
of alternative ways


540
00:24:20,526 --> 00:24:21,506
to avoid this problem.


541
00:24:22,266 --> 00:24:26,056
You could create your invitation
email URL that brings the user,


542
00:24:26,056 --> 00:24:28,836
first, back to your MDM
server before redirected them


543
00:24:28,836 --> 00:24:29,936
to the VPP URL.


544
00:24:30,906 --> 00:24:33,456
Or you could integrate the
invitation process right


545
00:24:33,456 --> 00:24:35,016
into your user portal
if you have one.


546
00:24:35,566 --> 00:24:39,796
Let's spend a few
moments talking, again,


547
00:24:39,796 --> 00:24:42,996
about user IDs relating to
Volume Purchase Program.


548
00:24:42,996 --> 00:24:44,306
I showed this slide last year.


549
00:24:44,916 --> 00:24:49,616
There are really 3 ideas of who
the user is from the perspective


550
00:24:49,616 --> 00:24:54,046
of the MDM server, from the
perspective of the VPP service,


551
00:24:54,446 --> 00:24:56,296
and the end user's Apple ID,


552
00:24:56,426 --> 00:25:00,416
which your MDM server will never
see directly but will see a hash


553
00:25:00,416 --> 00:25:02,246
of it to protect
the user's privacy.


554
00:25:03,246 --> 00:25:05,046
Now, this is would be
very simple if we lived


555
00:25:05,046 --> 00:25:08,066
in the ideal world
where each user had one


556
00:25:08,066 --> 00:25:11,376
and only one Apple ID
associated with your VPP account


557
00:25:11,816 --> 00:25:13,276
and would never change
that Apple ID.


558
00:25:13,276 --> 00:25:16,576
In this case, there would be
a simple one to one mapping


559
00:25:16,616 --> 00:25:19,196
between all 3 of these
representations of the user.


560
00:25:20,056 --> 00:25:22,126
Sadly, as many of
you may be aware,


561
00:25:22,256 --> 00:25:23,496
we don't live in an ideal world.


562
00:25:24,306 --> 00:25:28,236
In the real world, multiple
VPP users can accept their


563
00:25:28,236 --> 00:25:30,266
individual invitations
with the same Apple ID.


564
00:25:30,266 --> 00:25:32,736
And you need to be aware
of the implications


565
00:25:32,736 --> 00:25:34,506
of the sharing of Apple IDs.


566
00:25:35,086 --> 00:25:38,786
Specifically if you've
assigned a license to a user


567
00:25:38,786 --> 00:25:41,276
that than is connected to
that particular Apple ID.


568
00:25:41,576 --> 00:25:43,606
If you revoke that assignment,
it's going to revoke it


569
00:25:43,606 --> 00:25:47,156
from every Apple every VPP
user sharing that Apple ID.


570
00:25:48,416 --> 00:25:51,696
Also, if you try to
assign an app or a book


571
00:25:51,696 --> 00:25:55,966
to a VPP user that's
associated with an Apple ID


572
00:25:55,966 --> 00:25:59,276
that already has that
app or book assigned,


573
00:25:59,636 --> 00:26:02,546
that second assignment
will fail.


574
00:26:02,546 --> 00:26:05,736
Another issue in the real
world is that users can,


575
00:26:06,056 --> 00:26:08,606
after accepting an
invitation with one Apple ID,


576
00:26:08,606 --> 00:26:12,016
can disassociate from that Apple
ID and associate and accept


577
00:26:12,016 --> 00:26:13,786
that invitation with
a different Apple ID.


578
00:26:13,886 --> 00:26:16,956
This becomes a problem if you've
assigned any irrevocable book


579
00:26:17,326 --> 00:26:20,436
licenses to that Apple,
that retired Apple ID.


580
00:26:20,436 --> 00:26:23,296
And you'll have to keep track
and think about whether you want


581
00:26:23,296 --> 00:26:25,436
to allocate another
irrevocable book license


582
00:26:25,436 --> 00:26:26,726
to the new Apple ID or not.


583
00:26:30,426 --> 00:26:33,236
So the MDM server's
representation of the user,


584
00:26:33,236 --> 00:26:34,686
the client user ID string,


585
00:26:35,396 --> 00:26:37,076
is something that's
under your control.


586
00:26:37,076 --> 00:26:38,986
And we strongly recommend
you pick a value


587
00:26:38,986 --> 00:26:40,926
that will never change,
for example,


588
00:26:40,926 --> 00:26:42,836
the user ID from your
directory services


589
00:26:42,836 --> 00:26:45,056
where you're getting your
user and group information.


590
00:26:45,636 --> 00:26:46,446
You shouldn't choose something


591
00:26:46,446 --> 00:26:48,256
like an email address
which can change.


592
00:26:48,746 --> 00:26:51,276
And it's very simple.


593
00:26:51,276 --> 00:26:53,246
I had to have a slide with
some SQL on, I'm sorry.


594
00:26:53,246 --> 00:26:56,566
It's very easy, then, to
look up which VPP account


595
00:26:56,566 --> 00:26:59,896
that that particular MDM
user is associated with.


596
00:27:00,606 --> 00:27:02,886
Whether it's just registered
and you've sent the invitation


597
00:27:02,886 --> 00:27:05,746
or actually associated, whether
the user has accepted it.


598
00:27:06,256 --> 00:27:10,576
And, finally, the representation


599
00:27:10,576 --> 00:27:14,126
of the user's Apple ID who's
accepted the invitation takes


600
00:27:14,126 --> 00:27:16,186
the form of an iTunes
store ID hash.


601
00:27:16,786 --> 00:27:18,216
And you should track
this as soon


602
00:27:18,216 --> 00:27:20,136
as a user has accepted
an invitation.


603
00:27:21,106 --> 00:27:25,416
New in iOS 8, there's now a
MDM query, not just in iOS 8,


604
00:27:25,416 --> 00:27:29,386
it's also in OS X Yosemite, a
query to get that hash value


605
00:27:29,386 --> 00:27:35,096
so that you can know whether
the Apple ID that's configured


606
00:27:35,096 --> 00:27:36,966
on a particular device changes.


607
00:27:36,966 --> 00:27:39,276
You won't know exactly what the
Apple ID is but you'll be able


608
00:27:39,276 --> 00:27:40,836
to tell if they've disassociated


609
00:27:40,836 --> 00:27:43,326
and re-associated
with a different ID.


610
00:27:44,346 --> 00:27:46,726
As I mentioned already on the
previous slide, you're going


611
00:27:46,726 --> 00:27:50,866
to want to track those retired
values if the user switches


612
00:27:50,866 --> 00:27:53,706
to a different Apple ID,
again, so you can keep track


613
00:27:53,706 --> 00:27:55,456
of any irrevocable
book assignments.


614
00:27:55,896 --> 00:28:01,196
There's another new change
that will allow you MDM vendors


615
00:28:01,196 --> 00:28:03,766
to provide a better user
experience in your tools


616
00:28:03,876 --> 00:28:07,696
for users outside the U.S. that
we now report the country code


617
00:28:07,876 --> 00:28:10,726
that the account is tied to
when you get your information


618
00:28:10,726 --> 00:28:13,476
down from the service so that
you can fetch the proper app


619
00:28:13,476 --> 00:28:15,756
metadata, artwork, description,


620
00:28:15,756 --> 00:28:18,546
app name from the
correct iTunes Store.


621
00:28:21,806 --> 00:28:24,366
So managed apps is
not a new concept.


622
00:28:24,366 --> 00:28:26,276
We've had it for a
couple of iOS releases.


623
00:28:26,666 --> 00:28:30,626
It's a way for enterprises
to keep better control


624
00:28:30,626 --> 00:28:32,926
over the data and documents
tied to particular apps.


625
00:28:33,376 --> 00:28:36,026
It works with both App
Store and enterprise apps.


626
00:28:36,906 --> 00:28:39,916
The managed apps must
be installed via MDM


627
00:28:40,716 --> 00:28:42,296
with the install
application command


628
00:28:42,296 --> 00:28:45,686
and with the management
flag set on the app itself.


629
00:28:46,546 --> 00:28:49,286
One limitation is that if the
user has already installed an


630
00:28:49,286 --> 00:28:51,596
app, the MDM server
cannot convert it


631
00:28:51,596 --> 00:28:52,926
to manage retroactively.


632
00:28:53,506 --> 00:28:54,766
However, the server
can, of course,


633
00:28:54,766 --> 00:28:59,046
detect that an app is unmanaged
and then alert the administrator


634
00:28:59,046 --> 00:29:02,766
so they could take action
outside of MDM, if necessary,


635
00:29:03,176 --> 00:29:05,306
to have the user delete that app


636
00:29:05,306 --> 00:29:07,306
and the MDM server
push it out again.


637
00:29:08,636 --> 00:29:13,576
Managed apps work with Managed
Open In a new feature in iOS 7


638
00:29:13,956 --> 00:29:16,176
to help, again, prevent
data leakage


639
00:29:16,176 --> 00:29:19,026
from managed apps
to unmanaged apps.


640
00:29:19,806 --> 00:29:21,616
So that if you have
a particular app


641
00:29:21,706 --> 00:29:25,156
that has sensitive documents,
you can treat it as managed.


642
00:29:25,216 --> 00:29:28,216
Turn on Managed Open In, and
then users will not be able


643
00:29:28,216 --> 00:29:30,256
to open those documents
in other apps


644
00:29:30,256 --> 00:29:31,666
like well, I won't name any.


645
00:29:32,976 --> 00:29:35,166
So you might imagine, I
talked about filling gaps


646
00:29:35,166 --> 00:29:37,646
and eliminating inconsistencies.


647
00:29:37,646 --> 00:29:40,786
We have managed apps so what
are we introducing in iOS 8?


648
00:29:40,786 --> 00:29:42,646
Well, of course, managed books.


649
00:29:43,576 --> 00:29:46,326
And just like managed
apps, managed books works


650
00:29:46,326 --> 00:29:51,546
with both iBookstore books where
you can, just like managed apps,


651
00:29:52,146 --> 00:29:55,446
tell the device to download
a particular iBookstore book


652
00:29:55,446 --> 00:29:56,526
and treat it as managed.


653
00:29:57,316 --> 00:29:59,096
That that book must
be published,


654
00:29:59,266 --> 00:30:02,156
purchased via VPP even
if the user has it.


655
00:30:03,396 --> 00:30:07,126
One difference between managed
books and managed apps is


656
00:30:07,126 --> 00:30:09,756
that you can retroactively
manage books


657
00:30:09,756 --> 00:30:11,096
in contrast to manage apps.


658
00:30:11,096 --> 00:30:12,436
Even if the user
has it installed.


659
00:30:13,076 --> 00:30:15,566
This is very useful
in schools to ensure


660
00:30:15,566 --> 00:30:17,256
that a particular
title is installed,


661
00:30:17,346 --> 00:30:19,226
make sure the students
have all their work


662
00:30:19,226 --> 00:30:20,146
and the dog didn't eat it.


663
00:30:21,816 --> 00:30:27,286
Turning to enterprise books, you
can, just like enterprise apps,


664
00:30:27,286 --> 00:30:31,266
can install the MDM
and remove PDFs, ePubs,


665
00:30:31,266 --> 00:30:32,496
and iBooks Author books.


666
00:30:33,836 --> 00:30:36,746
These documents or
these titles are stored


667
00:30:36,746 --> 00:30:38,736
in a different location
than iBookstore books


668
00:30:39,246 --> 00:30:40,706
with Class C data protection.


669
00:30:41,806 --> 00:30:43,176
There are also a
number of restrictions


670
00:30:43,176 --> 00:30:45,096
that we're introducing
in iOS 8 to, again,


671
00:30:45,096 --> 00:30:48,896
give institutions
more confidence


672
00:30:48,896 --> 00:30:51,306
that the sensitive
data will be protected


673
00:30:51,306 --> 00:30:53,526
and not escape their control.


674
00:30:54,136 --> 00:30:57,496
They can disable iCloud backups
of these enterprise books


675
00:30:58,136 --> 00:31:00,276
so that they just stay on the
device where they're installed


676
00:31:00,866 --> 00:31:04,006
and also disable the
user's highlights and notes


677
00:31:04,006 --> 00:31:06,376
on that title from being
synced to other devices.


678
00:31:08,446 --> 00:31:09,966
For you MDM vendors out there,


679
00:31:09,966 --> 00:31:11,876
it's going to be pretty straight
forward to implement this.


